  "local_port": 56940,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do we forget any Wi-Fi in Windows 10?",
  "response": "Forgetting a Wi-Fi network in Windows 10 can help resolve connectivity issues, improve security, or remove networks you no longer use. Below are several methods to forget a Wi-Fi network:\n\n---\n\n### **Method 1: Using the Settings App**\n\n1. **Open Settings:**\n   - Click on the **Start** menu (Windows icon) in the lower-left corner of your screen.\n   - Select the **Settings** gear icon, or press `Windows + I` on your keyboard.\n\n2. **Navigate to Network Settings:**\n   - In the Settings window, click on **Network & Internet**.\n\n3. **Access Wi-Fi Settings:**\n   - From the left-hand sidebar, select **Wi-Fi**.\n\n4. **Manage Known Networks:**\n   - Click on **Manage known networks**. This will display a list of all Wi-Fi networks your computer has connected to in the past.\n\n5. **Forget the Desired Network:**\n   - Find the Wi-Fi network you want to forget in the list.\n   - Click on the network name to expand its options.\n   - Click the **Forget** button.\n\n   ![Forget Wi-Fi Network in Settings](https://i.imgur.com/UIrlV9r.png)\n\n6. **Confirmation:**\n   - The network will be removed from the list of known networks. Your PC will no longer automatically connect to it.\n\n---\n\n### **Method 2: Using the Control Panel**\n\n1. **Open Control Panel:**\n   - Press `Windows + R` to open the Run dialog box.\n   - Type `control` and press **Enter**.\n\n2. **Navigate to Network Settings:**\n   - Click on **Network and Internet**.\n   - Then select **Network and Sharing Center**.\n\n3. **Manage Wireless Networks:**\n   - In the left sidebar, click on **Manage wireless networks**. *(Note: This option may not be visible if you're using certain versions or updates of Windows 10. If unavailable, proceed with Method 1 or Method 3.)*\n\n4. **Forget the Desired Network:**\n   - Right-click on the Wi-Fi network you wish to forget.\n   - Select **Remove network** from the context menu.\n\n5. **Confirm Removal:**\n   - The selected network will be removed from your list of known networks.\n\n---\n\n### **Method 3: Using Command Prompt**\n\n1. **Open Command Prompt as Administrator:**\n   - Click on the **Start** menu.\n   - Type `cmd` in the search bar.\n   - Right-click on **Command Prompt** and select **Run as administrator**.\n\n2. **Display All Saved Wi-Fi Profiles:**\n   - In the Command Prompt window, type the following command and press **Enter**:\n     ```\n     netsh wlan show profiles\n     ```\n   - This will list all the Wi-Fi networks saved on your computer.\n\n3. **Forget a Specific Wi-Fi Network:**\n   - To remove a specific network, type the following command and press **Enter**:\n     ```\n     netsh wlan delete profile name=\"WiFi_Network_Name\"\n     ```\n     - Replace `\"WiFi_Network_Name\"` with the exact name of the Wi-Fi network you want to forget.\n     - **Example:**\n       ```\n       netsh wlan delete profile name=\"HomeWiFi\"\n       ```\n\n4. **Confirmation:**\n   - You should see a message indicating that the profile was successfully deleted.\n\n---\n\n### **Additional Tips**\n\n- **Reconnecting to a Forgotten Network:**\n  - If you wish to reconnect to a forgotten network in the future, select the network from the list of available Wi-Fi networks and enter the password when prompted.\n\n- **Automated Reconnection:**\n  - After forgetting a network, Windows 10 will no longer automatically connect to it. You can choose to reconnect manually when needed.\n\n- **Troubleshooting Connectivity Issues:**\n  - Forgetting and re-adding a Wi-Fi network can often resolve connectivity problems related to incorrect settings or corrupted profiles.\n\n---\n\nBy following any of the methods above, you can easily forget and remove unwanted Wi-Fi networks from your Windows 10 computer. Choose the method that you're most comfortable with or that best fits your situation.\n\nIf you encounter any issues or need further assistance, feel free to ask!",
